textDisplay:
Hola! Antes que nada, felicitaciones por tu proyecto, lo sigo desde el comienzo y me parece espectacular. Perdón por escribir en español, supongo que puedes traducirlo con el traductor automático de YouTube o con Google Translate.
Me pasa algo muy personal y particular con los gráficos y con la estética de N64. Es difícil de explicar, pero intentaré resumirlo: cuando llegó la N64 a latinoamérica, allá por los años 1997-1998, no entendíamos mucho de especificaciones técnicas, simplemente nos guiábamos por el número de bits de las consolas y por lo que vendían las publicidades. Si bien objetivamente N64 era superior a PlayStation 1 en muchos aspectos (no solo en la cantidad de bits), con el tiempo descubrí las limitaciones del formato cartucho, entre otras cuestiones que dejaban a N64 en desventaja con la ps1. Pero en aquel entonces, para mí N64 era sinónimo de superioridad en todos los aspectos. Entonces, mi mente (y mi corazón, si me lo permiten) hizo una especie de "asociación", y esa estética tan particular de N64 quedó grabada para siempre en mí como "los mejores gráficos que podrán existir jamás". Es hasta el día de hoy (2023) que sigo viendo los gráficos de N64, con esa "borrosidad" tan particular, esa niebla, esas texturas suavizadas, etc., y me siguen pareciendo INCREÍBLES. Obviamente sé que existen gráficos objetiva y técnicamente superiores, como los de la última edición de Xbox, PlayStation o Switch (o cualquier consola que salga en el futuro). Pero (y por eso decía al comienzo que era algo muy personal) para mí los gráficos de N64 siempre serán "superiores". Superiores para mí, porque me conectan con una época muy feliz de mi vida. Superiores porque eran los gráficos que veía en las vidrieras de los negocios de videojuegos, con la nariz pegada al vidrio, soñando recibir para Navidad el Super Mario 64 o el Ocarina of Time. Superiores porque todavía recuerdo la primera vez que tuve un mando de N64 en mis manos y no podía creer cómo se sentía. Superiores porque veía las publicidades de los juegos en la TV o en revistas y me parecían inalcanzables. Siempre digo que, paradójicamente, fueron aquellas limitaciones de la consola y del formato cartucho (que algunos señalan como puntos negativos) las que dieron como resultado y nos regalaron esa estética tan particular y única que tanto amamos. Larga vida a los gráficos de N64!!! Espero que se haya entendido mi punto. Saludos!

textDisplay:
The N64 had different styles from different devs. Later N64 games with more optimized microcode looked more like early PS2 games or perhaps PS1 games with texture filtering. Kazemanuar managed to speed up Mario 64's engine by several times with some additional optimization.

Note that PS1 textures also had to be smaller because you needed more geometry to reduce texture warping.

textDisplay: The N64 could still use textures larger than 64x64 pixels. There are several games later in the n64's lifecycle that use 128x textures (they are broken into 64x at runtime, but one 128x texture is a smaller file size than 4 64x textures).

textDisplay:
Man, oh man! I wish I'd found this video when it came out. A few months before it came out, I remember seeing some guy's project that was heavily modeled after the PS1/2's style, and it got me thinking "Why isn't there anything like this but for those of us who grew up in a Nintendo household?". I started researching the graphics pipeline and rendering hardware of the N64, and it just lead me down countless other rabbit holes. I remember a distinctive lack of "How to make N64 style graphics" videos. Even though I own a N64, and the ability to display its' content on both a CRT, and screen record for later reference, I could never get the style just right. It always felt like what I'd describe as "uncanny valley n64 graphics", it had a lot of the elements of n64 graphics, but something that I could never quite place my finger on was just off about it.

Since then, I've moved onto other projects in the realm of non-euclidean geometry. Given that, I don't think I'll have the time to return to such a project, but I'm really glad other people are both doing something with this idea, and creating resources for others who want to do the same. The future of 5th generation home console nostalgia is looking bright, and you are doing a tremendous job of being a core of that movement.

textDisplay: It's also important to keep in mind that N64 only had 4MB of RDRAM which is doubled to 8MB with the Expansion Pak. Even though the PS1 has more storage because of the CD, you only have 1MB of RAM, so you can't just load everything as you wish.

textDisplay:
2 questions:
1. I don't get how PS1 (or other consoles at the time) style is inferior to N64?
IMO, apples and oranges; Or 2 daughters with completely opposite personalities.
2. I get the economy and tradeoff for doing the old and new models, but how do you compensate for lighting behaviours like relectivity if you just have one material?
Today, halfway through setting up a final render for a lowpoly 3d model with pixelart texture, i realized the importance of separating UVs and materials for more control with light interaction.
(I'm building my skills to achieve what octopath traveler did for pixelart.)

today, halfway through setting up a final render for a lowpoly 3 d model with pixelart texture, i realized the importance of separating uvs and materials for more control with light interaction.
(i'm building my skills to achieve what octopath traveler did for pixelart.)

textDisplay: It's not the game medium that affected texture sizes on N64, it was actually just the amount of texture data the processor could hold at one time, which was 4 KB. You could fit at max 32x64 or 64x32 texture in the RGBA5551 format (2 bytes per pixel), 64x64 in the CI8 format (paletted texture) or 128x64/64x128 in the CI4 format (4 bits per pixel for each palette index)

textDisplay:
Former Dolphin Developer here

N64 used analytical edge AA based on Wu's line algorithm. Arguably it's more precise (at polygon edge AA) than most things done today (when it works). Contrary to popular belief it does not make N64 graphics less clear. To the contrary, it makes them more precise. What makes N64 slightly too blurry is the video interface blur added on top of the frame buffer to hide dither and further soften the parts where the AA did not work so well. That and many games just rendered at lower res and upscaled (what a precursor). Fortunately cheat codes/patches via flashcarts disable the dither filter, because they turn off the N64’s VI unit which is responsible for all post-processing effects. But the edge AA is great. Some devs even experimented doing something similar through shaders at the start of the current gen, but it's quality was restricted by lack of conservative rasterization hardware support. I still have wet dreams in which next gen analythical edge AA becomes a standard feature on next gen and I make sweet love to the TV screen, but I always wake up all exasperated right when things start to get real hot.

At their best N64 games looked significantly better than PS1 games, almost half a generation ahead. You can work around the tiny texture RAM but you just can't substitute for a lack of perspective correction or texture filtering. Lack of sub-pixel correction accuracy was the worst offender though. Lack of decent quality mipmapping/texture filtering, sub-pixel precision and perspective correction is just bad combination.

I think Star Wars Rogue Leader developer Julian Eggbrecht summed it up perfectly:
"A well done programmed N64 game always looks better than a similar PS1 game"

Hooking up my OSSC and going back and playing games on the PS1 is painful. Early N64 games were all really low res, but late games improved drastically and were far superior to that on the PS1, it's not even close.

Edit: Comparision starting at 0:20 is very missleading. While AA is enabled (0:27) so is the VI Unit which is responsible for that fuzzy screenshot. For all you who are wondering how AA on the N64 actually works:
Here's my own take captured with an OSSC (VI off, De-Blur off)
AA off https://imgur.com/a/au0lUmN
AA on https://imgur.com/a/tpS6DB6

Banjo Tooie is a good example as well (VI off, De-Blur off)
AA off https://imgur.com/a/VkFC4jF
AA on https://imgur.com/a/2eRKuiT

Some edges are smoothed out and artifacts eliminated. No difference in picture clarity. That stupid myth how N64's AA is supposed to work like FXAA, is some of the biggest nonsense I've ever read on the internet.

textDisplay:
Interesting video- good to see others taking an interest in this era of graphics. And I never noticed that smooth slope in Zelda before. Clever use of the filtering there!

A few things to add:
- You'll want to turn off shadows, as those are making the video look too modern! Most N64 games just used a dark circle under the character's feet, and maybe shaded certain areas of the map darker using vertex colours as well. A few standouts (e.g., Conker) used shadow maps, but the character models should be the only objects that cast shadows, and they should not be able to receive shadows themselves (Conker's head never casts a shadow across his chest, for example. Only on the environment.)

- The Nintendo 64 could only handle a few thousand triangles at a time: 1-2K for early or low-end games, and 5-10K for some really fancy ones.
If you want to keep the character models, draw distance, etc., really authentic, then hide everything that's not on camera, and see how many triangles are still being drawn.
This is where the tradeoffs come in: if you want a long draw distance, you'll have to keep the detail to a minimum. On the other hand, scripted cutscenes give you a lot of control over what is or isn't displayed, so you can put way more detail into the characters (see Kirby 64). The girl shown in the video really could appear in an N64 game without slowing it to a crawl, but probably not in such a big environment!

- The texture atlas makes sense for PS2 and newer, but not the N64. Not only is N64 starved for polygons already, but it has a small texture cache, which is the main reason so few games go beyond 64x64 with their textures. And if I'm not mistaken, it also performs better when it's just seamlessly tiling the same texture across a surface, as opposed to having someone manually choose the texture coordinates for each polygon, as the manual coordinates cause the N64 to essentially draw a bunch of individual polygons (which is slow) instead of one seamless strip. (Someone else may be able to explain that more concisely.)

textDisplay:
If you want a good example of how good an N64 game can look check out the recently leaked Dinosaur Planet, in some ways it looks better than the Gamecube version.

I think the only thing you missed is the N64's multitexture feature which let you blend 2 textures together at different resolutions and tiling and make a more varied pattern as a result. Often they'd throw a grayscale texture and a colored one together add variety. Not sure the best way to emulate it on modern engines.

The Grass in Hyrule Field in oot is an example of it though zelda and later n64 games use it a lot.

textDisplay: One thing I have noticed is that 'programmers' have effectively disappeared from the game industry.  In the old days you had people working around the clock to make the game work on extremely weak hardware while yielding impressive performance, to say nothing of people like John Carmack, but today you don't need to have any deep programming knowledge, just the ability to use Unreal or Unity.  Who cares if PS5 games look hardly any better than PS4 games, themselves barely any better than PS3 games, despite hardware being orders of magnitude stronger?  Who cares that a port of a literal PS2 game runs worse than other PS2 ports like San Andreas?  That problem is placed squarely on the consumer's shoulders.

textDisplay: One thing people always get wrong about N64 graphics is the resolution. Most people are used to playing games on emulators running in 1080p (or 720p at least) and they assume that a real N64 has sharp polygons with blurry low-res textures, which is just plain wrong. There aren't any N64 games that'll go past 480p on real hardware, and the look somewhat resembles PS1 since you don't have sharp models with blurry textures, everything is blurry. I suggest checking out the Angrylion's RDP Plus video plugin (it's rather heavy) on an emulator to get an idea of how the games actually look on real hardware (or just buy a N64) That aside, great job on the video, you got pretty close to the distinct N64 graphical style.

textDisplay:
A few notes about texture atlases.
1, you can avoid splitting the mesh in submeshes by manually implementing coordinate wrapping. It's not super easy and you're better off actually splitting the mesh, but it's a possibility
2, since you're using trilinear filtering you'll want to generate mipmaps. Always generate mipmaps by first shrinking down each texture individually, then stitch them in a smaller atlas
3, you can save yourself problems with the filtering by adding a one pixel border around every texture in the atlas. This will mean you need a bigger atlas for the same number of sub-textures, but it can avoid weird artifacts from filtering sampling neighbouring textures
4, if you're really committed to N64 graphics and limit yourself to the number of textures you'd have on the N64 at once, there's no point in using an atlas. Test on low-end hardware first and if you can't hit 60fps, then consider optimising.

3, you can save yourself problems with the filtering by adding a one pixel border around every texture in the atlas. This will mean you need a bigger atlas for the same number of sub-textures, but it can avoid weird artifacts from filtering sampling neighbouring textures
4, if you're really committed to N64 graphics and limit yourself to the number of textures you'd have on the N64 at once, there's no point in using an atlas. Test on low-end hardware first and if you can't hit 60fps, then consider optimising.

textDisplay:
Also worth noting is that modern displays can't replicate the look of CRT and we saw everything on CRT displays until around the mid-2000's. Picked one up recently and was astonished at how good it looks. It's only a matter of time until people forget what CRT gaming looked like. I already did.
Craiglists. Some guy giving away a 50" Sony SDTV for free. Picked it up behind his house a city away at 2am. Could barely lift the thing. Big risk too, it could've ruined the aesthetic of my rental unit since it takes up so much space. Sits angled beside my 60" 4k UHD with gaming PC.12 consoles connected to an AV splitter. Made the old SDTV smart too using a Roku 4k and HDMI to AC converter. Solid stuff. What's interesting is that SDTV's were actually capable of more vibrant colors compared to modern displays too. 90's Disney movies look better on an SDTV than in 4k.

textDisplay: @1:33 you mention that the larger PS1 textures are due to the expanded capabilities of CD storage, but as someone else mentioned, it's actually due to the fact that the N64 only had a total of 4k of texture cache to work with, which was why the textures ended up so small. AFAIK the 64x64 pixel textures on the N64 wasn't even a hard limit, it was simply the largest feasible size you could use in order to fit within the 4k cache.

textDisplay:
Hey! If you want to get N64 rendering in Unreal Engine 4, it's pretty tricky and there are no tutorials for this. But here's how I implement super basic N64 shading to make my UE4 games run smoothly and weight the less possible in android devices:
- Unlit materials.
- Textures multiplied by vertex colors so you can make baked lighting and shadows by painting vertices.
- Vertex lighting via materials for characters.


Unfortunately, as I said, there are no tutorials and no way to find anything of this on the internet by the easy way. So, I can say nothing but good luck!
